<dl id="n53095j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53095j">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53095j"> 95(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> the scanning / spot, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53095j"><li>FW 349.14 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53095j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53095j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53095j">MS BL 47480-63</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:107 <a name="mdd4" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd4.htm#n53095j">Draft: II.3&sect;4.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">TELEVISION TOPICS&mdash;collected by A. S. C1ark <p>&ldquo;Scanning&rdquo; causes an unavoidable loss of light. The picture is scanned in the normal way by a single spot, whether at the transmitting or the receiving end. This <mark>spot has to traverse the whole picture</mark> at regular and equal intervals. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The modulation then becomes visible on the screen as an image. In the liquid the waves produced by the element frequency on the quartz crystal are equivalent to one <mark>scanning spot</mark> on the screen. A large number of scanning spots are therefore used simultaneously. <small> <a name="PWT25dec37" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#PWT25dec37"><cite title="source">Populary Wireless and Television Times</cite></a> (25 December 1937) 393b,c</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
